3. Causes of Overfitting and Prevention Methods

Causes of Overfitting

Overfitting occurs when a machine learning model learns the training data too precisely, including random noise and irrelevant details. This typically happens when the model is excessively complex compared to the size and quality of the dataset. As a result, the model achieves high accuracy on training data but performs poorly on new, unseen data.

Prevention Techniques

Several techniques are commonly used to reduce overfitting:

Regularization: Penalizing overly complex models to limit extreme parameter values.

Cross-Validation: Evaluating the model across multiple subsets of data to ensure stable performance.

Feature Selection: Removing irrelevant or redundant features that add noise.

Increasing Dataset Size: More data helps the model learn general patterns rather than memorizing examples.


These techniques improve the model’s ability to generalize beyond the training dataset.


---

4. Training and Test Data Split and Its Importance

In machine learning, datasets are typically divided into training data and test data. The training set is used to build the model, while the test set is reserved for evaluating its performance on unseen data.

This separation is essential because evaluating a model on the same data used for training can lead to misleading conclusions. A model may appear accurate simply because it memorized the training data rather than learned generalizable patterns. By testing on separate data, researchers can better estimate how the model will perform in real-world scenarios.

Common practice involves allocating 70–80% of the data for training and the remainder for testing, depending on dataset size and problem complexity.


---

5. Case Study: Machine Learning in Healthcare

Case Study: Early Detection of Sepsis Using Machine Learning

A notable application of machine learning in healthcare is the early detection of sepsis, a life-threatening medical condition. Research published in Nature Medicine demonstrated that ML models trained on electronic health record data could identify early warning signs of sepsis hours before clinical diagnosis.

The study analyzed physiological signals such as heart rate, blood pressure, and laboratory results. By learning patterns from thousands of patient records, the model was able to predict sepsis onset earlier than traditional rule-based systems. The findings showed that machine learning has the potential to support clinicians by providing timely alerts, improving patient outcomes, and reducing mortality rates.


